<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1863-09-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1863-09-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="291" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d291">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Adams</persName>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 710.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1863-09-17"><hi rend="italic">September</hi> 17, 1863.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I now add to the number of similar cases
                            already intrusted to your charge that of the American bark Union Jack,
                            destroyed by the piratical vessel of British origin and equipment,
                            commonly designated the Alabama, and <pb facs="0464" n="422" xml:id="pg_422"/> will thank you to take such steps in the matter as
                            shall, in your judgment, tend to secure such redress as may be justly
                            due to the aggrieved parties from her Britannic Majesty’s
                            government.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Charles Francis Adams</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>